Please tell me, when we switch to dTAO, will 100% of all staked be in the root subnet at that moment? Does this mean that TAO will not be produced for some time until some TAO appears in the subnet pools?

And let's say the number of TAO in the root subnet = 5,000,000 TAO, and there are 1000 TAO in the pools. That is, a total of 5,001,000 TAO. Does this mean that each block will be created by 1 TAO and distributed among the pools of all subnets, depending on the emission of each subnet, or does it mean that 1000/5001000 = 0.000199960008 TAO will be minted, which will be sent to the subnet pools?
Will the alpha token be credited to the hot wallet every block? Or every epoch? Or once a day, as it is implemented now?

> Please tell me, when we switch to dTAO, will 100% of all staked be in the root subnet at that moment? 

yes

> Does this mean that TAO will not be produced for some time until some TAO appears in the subnet pools?

no, 1* tao will still be emitted each block

to answer your last part, root does not determine the emission rate. the emission rate for a subnet is based on the number of tao in the pool divided by the sum of tao across all pools (not including root). so starting off, there will be an equal amount of tao across all subnets i.e. 1 TAO per subnet. so the emission rates and prices will all start off equal. 64 subnets, so it would be 1/64 = 0.015625  (this is still subject to change. a new paper is coming out on friday that will have all the official details)
I think it's every epoch. should look similar to the old staking system, where you'd receive the rewards every 20mins or so

Thanks for the answer.

1 TAO will be emitted in each block if the number of TAO in all pools (excluding the root subnet) does not exceed the number of blocks since the launch of dTAO, right?

If TAO stops being emitted for this reason, will dTAO continue to be emitted every block?

At this moment due to root staking alpha price of any subnet goes down due to auto sell. While Tao in the pool increases (without auto sell). I continue to try to understand the logic of alpha in
Yeah with alpha diluting twice as fast it seems like nobody has incentive to buy in. Price just goes down over time

One consequence of alpha_in is that the constant inflation will kill off subnets that dont harness external demand for their SN tokens. 

Without alpha_in, a coordinated group of participants (SN owners, miners, valis) could hoard the alpha_out tokens and constrain supply, whilst their initial seeding of TAO into the pool would continuously receive TAO emissions, (artificially) driving up their alpha token price. 

Yes this group would still need to put TAO into the pools, or convince the market to, but its much easier to control SN token price if you can get as close to the inflation and hoard it. With alpha_in inflation into the pools, a Dutch auction like mechanism will help the broader ecosystem filter out SN's that cannot generate external demand for their tokens. 

Over-time this also shifts staker's incentive toward alpha pools, and away from root, as more dividends will be paid out to alpha, relatively

under the new system, there is no rule preventing the flow of TAO emissions

same with dTAO emissions. however, with the new system, the amount of alpha that flows in the pool can change depending on participation. the higher the participation i.e. people buying the token, the more alpha that flows to outstanding, which causes a lower amount of alpha to flow into the pool. but it still sums to 2. (by default, 1 in the pool and 1 to the subnet participants)

you can see this on testnet if you look at subnet 281. extremely high participation, with the vast majority of alpha held by users, and very little in the pool. so participants are rewarded heavily for their conviction. a consequence of this design however is that the liquidity for the pool slows down by a lot.

so a subnet can have a high market cap with high liquidity e.g. subnet 117 alfa. or it can have a high market cap with low liquidity e.g. subnet 281 dogetao

I would argue that you need alpha_in to incentivize new users to join, and to add more liquidity to the pool over time. 

like with subnet 281, it has low liquidity but the price is still high. and the system changes the flow of alpha_in to keep the price stable, without having to impact the tao_in.

the liquidity issue would be much worse if there were no alpha in at all.

yes, the alpha price will trend downwards for the most part, but the market value of your stake will trend upwards as the amount of tokens you earn outpaces the minor price drop. and the root sell pressure trends to 0 over time

this is a pretty cool idea but the subnets work a bit differently from tao, because tao is what is backing the value of the tokens. and you basically need the market to determine the price (and emissions) based on how much tao they are willing to put in the pool to receive the token in exchange

Appreciate above sharing of reasoning, we currently see a diverse number of subnets, as alpha is the subnets token, no (seed/private) sale funding can be attracted. Therefore effectively Tao emission to subnets is funding the development.

This results under dtao that subnet owners will sell alpha to pay for expenses. Same goes up for miners, which have operational cost while subnets don’t yet generate substantial income. 

Alpha in seems to quickly inflate away the funding possibilities of subnets at this stage of development.

Therefore root staking in this regards is taking away the funding for the subnets. As due to its auto sell it is diluting the conversion value of alpha.

Another solution is to not make root staking available

if the subnet wants funding, then they'll want people to buy the token, as that increases the price and emissions. the market is there to determine the price via staking & unstaking operations. and then the system works to stabilize the price, by adjusting the amount of alpha that flows into the pool.

it would be harder to attract funding if every alpha token went straight to the participants. you would have liquidity issues for each subnet pool. also, I think it would be easier for people to snipe and control the token early on if there was no alpha in.

in reality, for the first few months it will be chaotic, because the prices for every subnet token will trend to zero. so even if a subnet has high emissions (due to relatively high amount of tao in the pool compared to others), root will take away most of it for 60 to 80 days. it will be more about growing your alpha stake in that time. but carefully with dca.

The root in its current setup is value extracting from subnet stakeholders while adding no meaningful value or risk. The value extraction is from the actual builders. The parties we want to come in. It may be better to just allocate x% of Tao emissions directly to them if the protocol decides to reward current Tao holders.
I understand we need to go live so we need to fix the tech. This conversation therefore is also meant for v1.1

you buy the subnet token, and are now holding it. and you're staking with a vali to also earn emissions. root's proportion of the divs starts at 100% and then trends to 0 over time, with the crossover point (where root prop. is 50%) happening around 2 to 3 months in, depending on the amount of tao on root.

so as a nominator, the amount of divs you earn is extremely low at the start. because root is essentially this large nominator representing a large amount of alpha stake. and they are automatically swapping that alpha for tao every block. this is why it's better to dca, because you are buying what they are dumping into the pool.

giving tao directly to root (without this alpha -> tao conversion happening in the background) wouldn't work, because it wouldn't deter early actors from gaining too much power within the system

That is why we could let subnet owners set the weight for validator:miner:owner split in v1.1 this would counter the power of alpha owners as the staking rewards can be set relatively low, allowing sn owners to generate more alpha to distribute for Tao to fund building.

It also would incentivize subnet owners to make optimizations in validator code to reduce operating cost of validators.

The whole staking reward idea in my view needs to change, have you seen any growth company issuing “stock dividends”? At this moment stakers at root are extracting value from the ecosystem for being passive. (As in many other ecosystems). It is largely a waste of ecosystem resources.

People may ask, why then should I buy alpha if I don’t get staking rewards? You buy alpha as you expect the subnet to increase in value, like buying stocks.

the miners can also become nominators by moving some or all of their stake from their hotkey to a validator hotkey, and earn additional emissions that way.

It would make sense (to me) to use an exponential decay towards the minimum, starting from the `NetworkRateLimit` after last reg. Something like:
```
price = NetworkMinLockCost + (2*last_price-NetworkMinLockCost) * (1/2)^((block-last_block-NetworkRateLimit)/NetworkLockReductionInterval)
--> after NetworkRateLimit, price == last_price
--> after NetworkRateLimit+NetworkLockReductionInterval, price = NetworkMinLockCost*1/2 + last_price/2
--> after NetworkRateLimit+2*NetworkLockReductionInterval, price = NetworkMinLockCost*3/4 + last_price/4
--> after NetworkRateLimit+3*NetworkLockReductionInterval, price = NetworkMinLockCost*7/8 + last_price/8
--> until finally: price = NetworkMinLockCost
```

the basic idea is that

when price < emissions
tao_in equals the alpha price
and alpha_in = 1, which means alpha_out also equals 1
ex: if the price is 0.1 and emissions are 0.12, then the tao_in per block scales down to 0.1. this stabilizes the price.

and alpha_out increases, which means alpha_in decreases

when price > emissions, you decrease the flow of alpha_in at the right amount so that it stabilizes the price, without having to interrupt the tao emissions, like in the previous designs. as a consequence of this new design, the users within the subnet are rewarded more alpha. but it can slow down the alpha_in supply

Lets break it down.

Tao weight determines how quickly a subnet alpha becomes "active" in a subnet. The quicker we do that the faster it's dividend increases. The quicker we do that the faster we shift from the current validator set to the new set of validators in alpha. The quicker we do that the less economic security the subnet starts with (since the economic security of a subnet is proportional to the market cap required to perform a yuma attack).

The tao weight also determines how quickly prices reach a summation of 1. A lower tao weight will move us quicker to higher prices as the root selling will hold the prices below equilibrium because of auto outflow..
Ultimately the second point about equilibrium prices is actually hard to prove since optimal participants should likely restake on the expectation of converged prices.

TL;DR: 
High tao weight = lower initial prices and slow convergence from Bittensor 1.0 to Bittensor 2.0. 
Low tao weight = higher inital prices and faster convergence from Bittensor 1.0 to Bittensor 2.0
Note that the ~0.41 auto-sold alpha will represent a larger fraction of the pool now (because less alpha came in), so even more tao will flow to root-stakers.
